If you're thinking of watching this do yourself a favor and stab yourself in the face with a fork instead.  You'll be better off and probably smarter, even if you go deep enough to hit brain matter.  This is horrible.  I swear I wanted to see if it was really a movie, as I just wasn't convinced that it was.  I can tell you from the first three minutes that it does, indeed, appear to be movie length according to the little time bar on the bottom..  I can't even call that a positive thing to say as it feels like a form of torture to watch even the few minutes I watched.  I do sort of wonder what kind of person could sit through this entire thing.  I kind of hope I never meet any of those people.

There are some movies that are so bad they're good. This isn't one of them.

I believe it was Nietzsche who said "And if thou gaze long into an abyss, the abyss will also gaze into thee."

Anyway, this movie was free on Prime and my daughter wanted to watch it. I already knew it was bad. I didn't realize how bad.

I know how this character got its start on YouTube. I've heard the first two movies are awful too. But, the reaction I've had to this movie was visceral. That voice alone is enough.

I turned it off. I told my daughter that under no circumstances is she allowed to watch anything with the word "Fred" in the title, or any variation of that name. Which is good, because I'm proactively putting the nix on Freddie Got Fingered, which, by comparison, is a better movie.

Existential crisis? Absolutely. Maybe more like existential/cosmic horror. Just as gazing upon Cthulhu would drive you insane, so will this.

If you do not heed my advice, may God have mercy on your soul.

I am a 5th grade teacher, and my class recently earned an incentive which included a movie.  I showed them this movie, and they loved it.  I was appropriate and funny for my 10-11 year old students.  I was a little nervous about the name of the camp that Fred visited.  (Iwannapeepee)  That's about as close to the line as it got.  Fred's mother was quite a character too, but some of my students could relate.  :(  Bottom line, a good movie for pre-teen kids.  Older kids would probably find it too corny.

Man, what a disappointment. I was expecting big things from the final film in this trilogy, BIG THINGS. The jokes just fell flat this time around. The setup is quite promising; Fred gets sent to summer camp, but instead of going to Camp Superior, his mother sends him to Camp Iwanapeepee.  Don't get me wrong, some of the stuff super hilarious. As you would expect, Fred's voice is really funny, but it's just not enough to make up for some of the stupid jokes.
